title: 8-hydroxy-7-phenylpyrido[3,4-d]pyridazine-1,4-(2H,3H)-dione
paragraph: A mixture of 2 g. ethyl 5-hydroxy-6-phenylpyridine3,4-dicarboxylate. hydrochloride, 40 ml ethanol and 4 ml hydrazine hydrate was refluxed for 4 hours. After cooling, the pale yellow crystals were recovered by filtration, suspended in 20 ml of water and made acid with dilute hydrochloric acid. The crystals were recovered by filtration, rinsed with water and dried. The procedure provided 1.2 g of 8-hydroxy-7-phenylpyrido[3,4-d]pyridazine-1,4-(2H,3H)-dione, melting point: more than 300° C.

title: biphenyl
paragraph: Non-limiting examples of known compounds useful for the present invention wherein one R (R1) is H and the other (R2) is a substituted or unsubstituted phenyl group include 3,4-dihydroxy-5-phenyl-2(5H)-furanone (sometimes called 4-phenyl-2-hydroxytetronic acid); 3,4-dihydroxy-5-(4′-chlorophenyl)-2(5H)-furanone (sometimes called 4-(4′-chlorophenyl)-2-hydroxytetronic acid); 3,4-dihydroxy-5-(1′,2′-dihydroxyethyl)-2(5H)-furanone (sometimes called 4-dihydroxyethyl-2-hydroxytetronic acid); 3,4-dihydroxy-5-(4′methylpropylphenyl)-2(5H)-furanone; and 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(5-methylfur)-2-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone. As mentioned above, a subgroup bearing these substituents include compounds wherein R1 is H and R2 is a phenyl bearing another phenyl, forming a biphenyl, such as 3,4-dihydroxy-5-(1,1′-biphenyl)-2(5H)-furanone (sometimes called 4-biphenyl-2-hydroxytetronic acid); 3,4-dihydroxy-5-(4″-chlorobiphenyl)-2(5H)-furanone (sometimes called 4-chloro-biphe-nyl)-2-hydroxytetronic acid); 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[(4′-nitro-1,1′-biphenyl)-4-yl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[(4′-methyl-1,1′-biphenyl)-4-yl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[(2′,4′-dimethyl-1,1′-biphenyl)-4-yl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[(3′,4′-dimethyl-1,1′-biphenyl)-4-yl]-2(5H)-furanone; and 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[(4′-meth-oxy-1,1′-biphenyl)-4-yl]-2(5H)-furanone. In another subgroup of compounds, R1 is H and R2 is a phenyl substituted with a heteroaromatic (furyl or pyridyl) group such as, for example, 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(5-methylfur)-2-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(5-methylpyrid)-2-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(3-methylpyrid)-2-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(4-methylpyrid)-2-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(4-methylpyrid)-3-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone; 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(5-methylpyrid)-3-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone; and 3,4-dihydroxy-5-[4-(2-methylpyrid)-3-yl)phenyl]-2(5H)-furanone.

title: 1,2-Bistrifluoromethylsulfonyloxyethane
paragraph: Preparation and handling of organometallic compounds were carried out in the absence of air and moisture under argon (Schlenk technique or glove box). All solvents required were purged with argon and dried over molecular sieves before use. 1,2-Bistrifluoromethylsulfonyloxyethane was synthesized as described by Lindner, Ekkehard; Au, Guenter von; Eberle, Hans-Juergen; Chem.Ber.; 114; 2; 1981; 810-813. The preparations of 1,3-bistrifluoromethylsulfonyloxypropane and 1,2-bistrifluoromethylsulfonyloxycyclohexane were carried out analogously. The indenes used were prepared as described in WO 9840331.

title: N-(5-isopropyl-1,3-thiazol-2-yl)-2-[2-(2-oxo-1-pyrrolidinyl)-1,3-thiazol-4-yl]acetamide
paragraph: A mixture of 2.8 g (0.01 mol) of 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-N-(5-isopropyl-1,3-thiazol-2-yl)acetamide, 4.84 g (0.02 mol) of ethyl-iodobutyrate and 2.76 g (0.02 mol) of potassium carbonate in 50 ml of absolute ethanol was stirred under reflux for 5 hours. The mixture was cooled and filtered, and the salts were washed with two 20 ml portions of ethanol. The ethanol was removed at reduced pressure and the residue was dissolved in 100 ml of CH2Cl2. The solution was washed with 30 ml of water, dried, and the solvent was evaporated. The residue was purified by chromatography on silica gel, using CH2Cl2:MeOH 95:5 as eluent, to give the title compound in 30% yield (1.05 g).

title: Preparation of 2-Benzylideneamino Glycine Ethyl Ester
paragraph: To a 2 L flask, equipped with an overhead stirrer, was added 101.1 g of glycine ethyl ester hydrochloride salt (1.05 eq), 82.1 g magnesium sulfate (1.0 eq), 0.5 L acetonitrile, 72.7 g benzaldehyde (1.0 eq), and 138.7 g triethylamine (2 eq). The reaction mixture was stirred at 20-25° C. for ˜4 h. The solid was filtered off, and washed with 2×0.1 L acetonitrile. The crude product (filtrate) was ready for use in the next step.
